Izanagi and Izanami decided to ascend to heaven and consult the primordial gods at [[Takamagahara]] about the ill-formed children that resulted from their union. The gods determined through divination that the female speaking first during the ceremony was the cause. So the couple returned to Onogoroshima island and repeated the rite encircling the column, only making sure Izanagi was the first to speak out in greeting. When finished, they performed the union successfully and lands began to be born.<ref name="kojiki-p75">{{Harvnb|Chamberlain|2008|p=75}}</ref>

====Birth of the islands====
According to the legend, the formation of Japan began with the creation of eight large islands by Izanagi and Izanami. In order of birth these islands are the following:<ref name="kojiki-p75"/>
[[File:Japan yashima.png|right|220px]]
# {{nihongo|'''Awaji-no-ho-no-sawake-no-shima'''|淡道之穂之狭別島}}: currently, [[:en:Awaji Island|Awaji Island]];
# {{nihongo|'''Iyo-no-futana-no-shima'''|伊予之二名島}}: currently, [[Shikoku]]. This island had a body and four faces. The names of the faces are as follows:
#:* {{nihongo|'''Ehime'''|愛比売}}: [[:en:Iyo Province|Iyo Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''Ihiyorihiko'''|飯依比古}}: [[:en:Sanuki Province|Sanuki Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''[[Ohogetsuhime]]'''|大宣都比売}}: [[:en:Awa Province (Tokushima)|Awa Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''Takeyoriwake'''|建依別}}: [[:en:Tosa Province|Tosa Province]].
# {{nihongo|'''Oki-no-mitsugo-no-shima'''|隠伎之三子島}}: today, [[:en:Oki Islands|Oki Islands]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Ame-no-oshikorowake'''|天之忍許呂別}};
# {{nihongo|'''Tsukushi-no-shima'''|筑紫島}}: today, [[Kyushu|Kyūshū]]. This island had a body and four faces. The names of the faces are as follows:
#:* {{nihongo|'''Shirahiwake'''|白日別}}: [[:en:Tsukushi Province|Tsukushi Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''[[Toyohiwake]]'''|豊日別}}: [[:en:Toyo Province|Toyo Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''Takehimukahitoyokujihinewake'''|建日向日豊久士比泥別}}: [[:en:Hi Province|Hi Province]];
#:* {{nihongo|'''Takehiwake'''|建日別}}: [[Kumaso]].
# {{nihongo|'''Iki-no-shima'''|伊伎島}}: today, [[Iki Island]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Amehitotsubashira'''|天比登都柱}};
# {{nihongo|'''Tsu-shima'''|津島}}: today, [[Tsushima Island]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Ame-no-sadeyorihime'''|天之狭手依比売}};
# {{nihongo|'''Sado-no-shima'''|佐度島}}: today, [[Sado Island]];
# {{nihongo|'''Ohoyamatotoyoakitsu-shima'''|大倭豊秋津島}}: today, [[Honshu]].  Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Amatsumisoratoyoakitsunewake'''|天御虚空豊秋津根別}}.

Traditionally these islands are known as [[:en:Ōyashima|Ōyashima]] (lit. eight large islands) and as a whole are what is currently known as Japan. In the myth neither [[:en:Hokkaidō|Hokkaidō]] nor the [[:en:Ryukyu Islands|Ryukyu Islands]] are mentioned as these were not known to the Japanese at the time of compiling the Kojiki.<ref name="kojiki-p75"/>

Additionally, Izanagi and Izanami then gave birth to six islands:<ref name="kojiki-p75"/><ref name="kojiki-p76">{{Harvnb|Chamberlain|2008|p=76}}</ref>
# {{nihongo|'''Kibi-no-kojima'''|吉備児島}}: {{ill|Kojima Peninsula|2=ja|3=児島半島|preserve=1|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojima Peninsula|qq=|1=Kojima Peninsula|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11388656}} of [[:en:Kibi Province|Kibi]] (now in [[:en:Okayama Prefecture|Okayama]]). Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Takehikatawake'''|建日方別}};
# {{nihongo|'''Azuki-jima'''|小豆島}}: [[:en:Shōdoshima|Shōdoshima]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Ohonodehime'''|大野手比売}};
# {{nihongo|'''Oho-shima'''|大島}}: [[:en:Suō-Ōshima|Suō-Ōshima]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Ohotamaruwake'''|大多麻流別}};
# {{nihongo|'''Hime-jima'''|女島}}: [[:en:Hime Island, Japan|Himeshima]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Amehitotsune'''|天一根}};
# {{nihongo|'''Chika-no-shima'''|知訶島}}: [[:en:Gotō Islands|Gotō Islands]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Ame-no-oshio'''|天之忍男}};
# {{nihongo|'''Futago-no-shima'''|両児島}}: [[:en:Danjo Islands|Danjo Islands]]. Dubbed {{nihongo|'''Amefutaya'''|天両屋}}.

